tables.Name: Prime - Parry 1
tables.Description (foil and \u00e9p\u00e9e): Blade down and to the inside, wrist pronate d. Sometimes known as the "Looking at your watch" Parry.
tables.Description (sabre): Blade points down and "cutting edge" faces away from the fencer's chest side. To stop low-line cut to chest.
tables.Diagram: thumb|Illustration of the prime parry (from Roworth's manual of defense 1798)<ref>Roworth, Charles, ''The Art of Defence on Foot with the Broadsword and Sabre, uniting the Scotch and Austrian methods into one Regular System,'' 1798 ([http://swordfight.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/Art-of-Defence-on-Foot-Second-Edition.pdf 2nd edition])</ref>.

tables.Name: Seconde - Parry 2
tables.Description (foil and \u00e9p\u00e9e): Blade down and to the outside, wrist pronated.
tables.Description (sabre): Arm half-extended laterally, blade pointing forward with downward incline, cutting edge facing away fencer's flank side. To stop low-line cut to flank.

tables.Name: Tierce - Parry 3
tables.Description (foil and \u00e9p\u00e9e): Blade up and to the outside, wrist pronated.  Not often used in Foil, and in Épée only as a block to wrist flicks.
tables.Description (sabre): Standard en garde but rotated so cutting edge faces further in the flank direction, i.e. guard kept low, sword upright with a slight forward tilt, cutting edge facing 45° to the outside. To stop outside high-line cut to flank or shoulder.
tables.Diagram: x400px |The tierce parry in sabre (from Hutton 1889)<ref name=Hutton1889>Hutton, Alfred,''[https://www.scribd.com/document/276222882/Cold-Steel-a-Practical-Treatise-on-the-Sabre-Alfred-Hutton-1889 Cold Steel: a Practical Treatise on the Sabre],'' Clowes and Sons, London, 1889.  See also version at [http://wiki.meyerfreescholars.com/index.php/Hutton_Sabre  Meyer Free Scholars].  Retrieved 25 June 2019.</ref>

tables.Name: Quarte - Parry 4
tables.Description (foil and \u00e9p\u00e9e):
Blade up and to the inside, wrist supinate d. de Beaumont, C.L. Fencing: Ancient Art and Modern Sport , 1960. p. 68. This parry can be Lateral or Circular, as can most all parries.

The Contre Parry.
The Circular Parry, also known as "Contre Quarte", is a circular or oval shape. It begins in either the neutral or quarte position, and with a twist of the wrist it ends in the carte parry.
tables.Description (sabre): Similar to tierce on the chest side or prime flipped upside-down; guard low, cutting edge facing away from chest, sword upright with slight chest-direction tilt. To stop high-line cut to chest.

tables.Name: Quinte - Parry 5
tables.Description (foil and \u00e9p\u00e9e): Blade up and to the inside, wrist pronated. de Beaumont, C.L. Fencing: Ancient Art and Modern Sport , 1960. p. 71. Not often used in Foil or Épée
tables.Description (sabre): Blade held up almost horizontally with bent arm, cutting edge facing upward and forward, blade has a slight tilt meaning that the point is higher than the guard. To stop cut to head.
tables.Diagram: thumb|120px|Parry quinte in sabre (from Patten's 1861 manual)<ref>Patten, George, ''Patten’s Cavalry Drill and Sabre Exercise, Compiled Agreeably to the Latest Regulations of the War Department,'' J. W. Fortune, NY, October 1861 ([http://www.mainecav.org/library/pattens_cavalry_drill_and_sabre_exercise.pdf 1864 edition])</ref>.

tables.Name: Sixte - Parry 6
tables.Description (foil and \u00e9p\u00e9e):
Blade up and to the outside, wrist supinated. 
This parry can be Lateral or Circular.

The Lateral Parry is from Quarte to Sixte.
The Circular Parry, also known as "Contra Sixte", is a D-shaped parry, dropping the points and bringing it up on the inside bringing your point back towards your En Guard line.
tables.Description (sabre): The arm position is a mirror image of quinte (supinated, forearm vertical on the quarte side of the head). Point is diagonal across the body covering the head, but towards the opponent, and slightly upwards (or forwards for a direct riposte in opposition). To stop cut to head.  (Rarely or never used in modern sabre)

tables.Name: Septime - Parry 7
tables.Description (foil and \u00e9p\u00e9e):
Blade down and to the inside, wrist supinated.  Point dropped, the wrist is in the same place as in Quarte. 
This parry is semi-circular, the point is dropped from Quarte to Septime (or the opposite).
tables.Description (sabre): Very similar to Tierce, but the blade is held upside down, with the palm facing and being level with the temple. To stop cut to the flank and back. (Rarely used in modern sabre)

tables.Name: Octave - Parry 8
tables.Description (foil and \u00e9p\u00e9e):
Blade down and to the outside, wrist supinated. Point is dropped, the wrist is in the same place as in Sixte. 
This parry is semi-circular, the point is dropped from Sixte to Octave (or the opposite).

tables.Name: Neuvieme - "Parry 9"
tables.Description (foil and \u00e9p\u00e9e): In addition to the eight classic parries, several parries are proposed as "parry nine".  It is usually considered a parry that protects the back, point down. Scandaglio, [http://www.scandaglio.nl/fulldict.html Fencing Dictionary] .  See also [http://www.synec-doc.be/escrime/dico/engl.htm Glossary of terms] . (accessed 27 Jan 2015) Glise, Anthony L., Beginning Foil Fencing — In Practice and Combat, Aevia Publications, 2005. p. 15.
